    The mathematical point, Non-Q forms, Q-form field, substance, and other fundamental concepts

    A mathematical point is the minimal locus of vectorial structure in potency, not yet expressed as magnitude or direction. A point with no vector is an unactualized structure—a limiting abstraction, much like “nothingness.” Based on this, we can state the following:

    Q-form is the immaterial source of mathematical points, providing the potential for the physical field of force vectors, which can be structured and actualized by non-Q forms (formal principles). Q-form is required only when a form is to be actualized as a physical field. >>> raw Q.form substance

    Non-Q form is the immaterial structural principle that organizes and directs potentialities, providing the blueprint for both conscious and physical actualizations. Non-Q forms structure Q-form when a physical field is to be instantiated, or guide ideation and perception when the form is realized in consciousness. Non-Q forms are required whenever a potential is to be formalized into a coherent structure, whether mental or material.

    Non-Q subsistent forms are self-subsisting forms endowed with intentional and deliberative consciousness; all other forms lack subsistence and agency—that is, intentionality, rational deliberation, and self-directed formal causation—and exist only informationally in the Matrix or as dependent structures requiring actualization.

    Substance:
        Self-subsisting substance:
            A. Complete substance: exists independently and does not require Q-form to be fully operative — angel
            B. Incomplete substance: exists independently and requires Q-form to be fully operative — human soul

        Non-self-subsisting substance: does not exist independently and requires Q-form to be operative — shoe, bee

